1
00:00:00,620 --> 00:00:14,610
And that's the emphasis we're going to go with. And so this morning, we're going to begin with probably the toughest question of them all, and that is this. Why does evil exist at all?

2
00:00:17,080 --> 00:00:23,640
Let me start off this series with a couple of quotes this morning. From George H. Smith, the atheist, he writes this.

3
00:00:24,880 --> 00:00:29,040
Christian theism, he says, must be rejected by any person

4
00:00:29,040 --> 00:00:32,360
with even a shred of respect for reason.

5
00:00:33,750 --> 00:00:35,150
How does that make you feel if you're a believer?

6
00:00:37,760 --> 00:00:41,480
And yet Patrick Glynn, an atheist turned Christian, wrote this.

7
00:00:42,360 --> 00:00:46,460
Today it seems to me there is no good reason for an intelligent person

8
00:00:46,460 --> 00:00:51,360
to embrace the illusion of atheism or agnosticism,

9
00:00:51,800 --> 00:00:54,340
to make the same intellectual mistakes I made.

10
00:00:54,340 --> 00:00:58,780
I wish I had known then what I know now.

11
00:01:00,240 --> 00:01:04,920
Two completely different perspectives on this issue of truth and God

12
00:01:04,920 --> 00:01:08,640
and the whole issues that were coming up in the coming weeks.

13
00:01:09,260 --> 00:01:12,040
Our position, as we're going to see as we unfold this,

14
00:01:12,300 --> 00:01:15,240
is that Christianity is a faith based on history

15
00:01:15,240 --> 00:01:18,860
and is a faith that meets the intellectual, the spiritual,

16
00:01:19,080 --> 00:01:21,100
and the emotional needs of human beings.

17
00:01:21,440 --> 00:01:23,600
It has mystical elements to it.

18
00:01:23,600 --> 00:01:31,960
Part of the Christian faith is a mystical experience, but it is also a reasonable, rational, intelligible faith.

19
00:01:32,980 --> 00:01:37,400
And so we come to the first of eight classic challenges to the Christian faith.

20
00:01:37,560 --> 00:01:43,540
And the first one this morning is what is classically determined as the problem of evil.

21
00:01:44,340 --> 00:01:49,020
The reality of evil in the world, if God is supposed to be a good God.

22
00:01:50,020 --> 00:01:53,860
Epicurus, an ancient philosopher, he wrote these words, and I share them with you.

23
00:01:54,480 --> 00:01:59,040
He wrote, either God wants to abolish evil and cannot,

24
00:01:59,820 --> 00:02:05,880
or he can but does not want to, or he cannot and does not want to.

25
00:02:06,360 --> 00:02:08,980
If he wants to but cannot, he is impotent.

26
00:02:09,380 --> 00:02:12,300
If he can and does not want to, he is wicked.

27
00:02:12,300 --> 00:02:18,140
But if God both can and wants to abolish evil, then how comes evil in the world?

28
00:02:18,540 --> 00:02:19,820
That's the question.

29
00:02:21,340 --> 00:02:24,420
I would posit to say that we've all experienced evil in some way.

30
00:02:24,940 --> 00:02:27,280
Whether it was the betrayal of a friend,

31
00:02:27,380 --> 00:02:28,320
whether you were young,

32
00:02:28,420 --> 00:02:30,420
or whether something in the business world.

33
00:02:30,980 --> 00:02:32,720
We've all suffered in different ways.

34
00:02:32,840 --> 00:02:34,660
We've had hurts and pains in different ways.

35
00:02:35,040 --> 00:02:37,080
And then, of course, we can extrapolate and go further.

36
00:02:37,440 --> 00:02:39,600
There are the big evils, like the Holocaust,

37
00:02:40,540 --> 00:02:41,840
the killing fields of Cambodia,

38
00:02:42,800 --> 00:02:44,040
the genocide in Rwanda.

39
00:02:44,040 --> 00:02:46,560
Turn on ABC, CNN, or Fox News,

40
00:02:46,560 --> 00:02:50,320
and you'll get to hear a litany of every night of evil

41
00:02:50,320 --> 00:02:53,060
constantly dripping through your family room.

42
00:02:54,030 --> 00:02:56,890
If God is loving and all-powerful and he is good,

43
00:02:57,210 --> 00:03:00,670
then all this evil we seem to want to say should not exist.

44
00:03:01,510 --> 00:03:03,310
And yet if we're honest, we know that it does.

45
00:03:04,130 --> 00:03:06,490
How do you make sense out of this?

46
00:03:08,210 --> 00:03:10,650
The answer that many come to is there simply is no God.

47
00:03:11,430 --> 00:03:14,790
For obviously they say God would not allow evil to exist

48
00:03:14,790 --> 00:03:16,170
if he had the power to stop it.

49
00:03:16,170 --> 00:03:19,410
and if He indeed was truly a good God.

50
00:03:20,030 --> 00:03:22,930
The other option is that God is indeed evil

51
00:03:22,930 --> 00:03:24,530
or somehow malevolent.

52
00:03:25,050 --> 00:03:27,070
That He takes some sick pleasure

53
00:03:27,070 --> 00:03:28,930
in watching people suffer.

54
00:03:30,190 --> 00:03:31,290
And then when people say that,

55
00:03:31,350 --> 00:03:32,990
obviously He's not worthy of worship.

56
00:03:34,660 --> 00:03:36,240
Or simply this, the third option,

57
00:03:36,240 --> 00:03:39,180
is that God, He can't quite eradicate evil.

58
00:03:39,720 --> 00:03:41,220
He's not quite able.

59
00:03:41,340 --> 00:03:43,380
He's not quite in control of all things.

60
00:03:43,880 --> 00:03:46,240
Some things are out of His control,

61
00:03:46,420 --> 00:03:47,160
some would say.

62
00:03:48,900 --> 00:03:51,780
And yet I'm going to say the biblical revelation says

63
00:03:51,780 --> 00:03:54,980
that God is indeed good and all-powerful.

64
00:03:55,280 --> 00:03:56,880
And I want to work from that position.

65
00:03:57,200 --> 00:03:59,460
And some scriptures to back that up would be this.

66
00:03:59,740 --> 00:04:01,740
Exodus chapter 34, verse 6.

67
00:04:02,800 --> 00:04:05,060
The Bible says he passed in front of Moses

68
00:04:05,060 --> 00:04:08,560
and said, I am the Lord, I am the Lord,

69
00:04:08,940 --> 00:04:10,820
the merciful and the gracious God.

70
00:04:10,820 --> 00:04:15,920
I am slow to anger and rich in unfailing love and faithfulness.

71
00:04:17,060 --> 00:04:21,220
And the book of Nahum, perhaps not always read, but has this little gem.

72
00:04:22,080 --> 00:04:24,360
Verse 7, the Lord is good.

73
00:04:25,100 --> 00:04:27,300
When trouble comes, he is a strong refuge.

74
00:04:27,600 --> 00:04:30,880
And he knows everyone who trusts in him.

75
00:04:30,880 --> 00:04:36,640
That is just a sampling of myriad of verses that tell of the goodness of God.

76
00:04:38,810 --> 00:04:41,170
There are verses that also talk about God's power.

77
00:04:43,190 --> 00:04:47,880
Genesis 1.1, in the beginning, God created the heavens.

78
00:04:48,740 --> 00:04:53,470
and the earth. I don't think there's anything more powerful than that verse to say that

79
00:04:53,470 --> 00:04:59,290
God is powerful to create all that we experience, the heavens and the earth, God is responsible

80
00:04:59,290 --> 00:05:07,610
for creating. In Jeremiah 32, I am the Lord, the God of all the peoples of the world. Is

81
00:05:07,610 --> 00:05:16,720
anything too hard for me? As biblical Christians, we need to start with the assumption that

82
00:05:16,720 --> 00:05:19,140
God is indeed good and all-powerful.

83
00:05:19,420 --> 00:05:24,540
And that then brings us back to the question then, if that is true, then why does evil

84
00:05:24,540 --> 00:05:25,240
exist?

85
00:05:26,740 --> 00:05:28,780
Well, let's talk about evil for a few moments.

86
00:05:29,670 --> 00:05:32,270
It's hard to describe exactly what it is.

87
00:05:32,270 --> 00:05:37,430
We can all say we've experienced it, and yet what is it really?

88
00:05:38,870 --> 00:05:43,110
So my first point this morning, I want to just touch on what is evil?

89
00:05:43,270 --> 00:05:45,390
What is the nature of evil?

90
00:05:45,710 --> 00:05:47,690
First of all, I want to say something about this,

91
00:05:47,890 --> 00:05:49,770
that the very existence of evil

92
00:05:49,770 --> 00:05:53,230
can actually be used to bolster the argument

93
00:05:53,230 --> 00:05:55,070
that God exists.

94
00:05:55,270 --> 00:05:56,190
Have you ever thought of it that way?

95
00:05:56,850 --> 00:05:58,370
The mere fact that evil exists

96
00:05:58,370 --> 00:06:01,750
can actually point to the fact that God exists.

97
00:06:01,810 --> 00:06:02,810
And here's how it works.

98
00:06:03,510 --> 00:06:05,790
We tend to have this outrage

99
00:06:05,790 --> 00:06:07,950
at the presence of evil.

100
00:06:07,950 --> 00:06:09,990
When we get angry at evil,

101
00:06:10,860 --> 00:06:12,500
we are saying that there is something

102
00:06:12,500 --> 00:06:14,740
that is different from evil that is good.

103
00:06:15,340 --> 00:06:17,940
We're somehow saying if we're outraged at evil,

104
00:06:18,140 --> 00:06:21,560
we're distinguishing it from what is good.

105
00:06:23,550 --> 00:06:26,010
We're saying that evil and good both exist,

106
00:06:26,770 --> 00:06:27,890
and yet they are separate.

107
00:06:28,290 --> 00:06:29,370
And if that is true,

108
00:06:29,970 --> 00:06:31,890
then what is the supreme standard

109
00:06:31,890 --> 00:06:33,370
by which we make that determination?

110
00:06:33,870 --> 00:06:37,110
How do we decide this is good and this is evil?

111
00:06:37,310 --> 00:06:40,290
How do we get outraged at evil if there is no good?

112
00:06:40,550 --> 00:06:41,530
And the question becomes,

113
00:06:41,830 --> 00:06:45,170
where do we get the idea of that supreme good?

114
00:06:46,260 --> 00:06:48,640
The supreme good, I would posit, is this.

115
00:06:49,020 --> 00:06:50,820
We'll call him God.

116
00:06:52,700 --> 00:06:53,360
It's God himself.

117
00:06:55,950 --> 00:06:57,850
We're outraged at this notion of evil.

118
00:06:58,370 --> 00:06:59,590
We rail against it.

119
00:06:59,710 --> 00:07:01,650
We struggle with the reality.

120
00:07:01,990 --> 00:07:02,890
But what is it?

121
00:07:03,310 --> 00:07:05,630
Well, evil is not a substance.

122
00:07:05,830 --> 00:07:06,730
It's not a thing.

123
00:07:06,810 --> 00:07:09,890
It's not something you can easily grab your hands around.

124
00:07:09,890 --> 00:07:12,770
It's not something that's created per se.

125
00:07:13,210 --> 00:07:16,270
Evil can be thought of, and the classical theologians would concur,

126
00:07:16,270 --> 00:07:19,290
that it's a lack of some good thing.

127
00:07:20,720 --> 00:07:22,220
The Old Testament thinks of evil

128
00:07:22,220 --> 00:07:25,440
in terms of the vandalism of shalom.

129
00:07:25,660 --> 00:07:27,240
Shalom being goodness

130
00:07:27,240 --> 00:07:29,020
and the way things ought to be.

131
00:07:30,140 --> 00:07:32,200
Shalom is peace and harmony.

132
00:07:33,550 --> 00:07:35,170
And yet evil distorts that.

133
00:07:35,290 --> 00:07:36,390
It contorts it

134
00:07:36,390 --> 00:07:39,420
and distorts what ought to be.

135
00:07:40,300 --> 00:07:42,580
To borrow an idea from Dr. Cornelius Plantinga,

136
00:07:42,580 --> 00:07:45,460
evil perverts, it pollutes,

137
00:07:45,460 --> 00:07:48,760
and it disintegrates shalom.

138
00:07:50,030 --> 00:07:51,370
I'm going to show you a clip in a moment.

139
00:07:52,100 --> 00:07:53,700
It comes out of a film in the early 90s

140
00:07:53,700 --> 00:07:54,600
called Grand Canyon.

141
00:07:55,040 --> 00:07:56,420
Danny Glover and this one other character

142
00:07:56,420 --> 00:07:58,900
are discussing this problem of evil

143
00:07:58,900 --> 00:08:00,860
in a very practical way.

144
00:08:01,180 --> 00:08:03,660
And I want you to hear the theologian, if you will,

145
00:08:04,180 --> 00:08:06,200
Danny Glover, this morning, to show the scene.

146
00:08:16,300 --> 00:08:18,160
You've got to answer one more thing for me

147
00:08:18,160 --> 00:08:19,420
and you've got to tell me the truth.

148
00:08:20,330 --> 00:08:22,570
Are you asking me a favor as a sign of respect?

149
00:08:23,380 --> 00:08:25,620
Or are you asking me a favor because I've got the gun?

150
00:08:25,700 --> 00:08:37,580
World ain't supposed to work. I mean, maybe you don't know that, but this ain't the way it's supposed to be.

151
00:08:37,720 --> 00:08:42,120
I'm supposed to be able to do my job without asking you if I can't.

152
00:08:42,620 --> 00:08:46,270
That dude is supposed to be able to wait with his car without you ripping him off.

153
00:08:47,380 --> 00:08:49,380
Everything's supposed to be different than what it is.

154
00:08:52,760 --> 00:08:55,180
Everything's supposed to be different than the way it is.

155
00:08:55,940 --> 00:08:58,860
What he's saying there is very powerful and very profound.

156
00:08:58,860 --> 00:09:01,000
that what's happening in this scenario

157
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:03,720
as he's coming to take the car away

158
00:09:03,720 --> 00:09:05,520
to the shop and get it fixed

159
00:09:05,520 --> 00:09:07,180
and these guys are gathering around the car

160
00:09:07,180 --> 00:09:08,460
waiting to rip off the owner

161
00:09:08,460 --> 00:09:11,580
he's saying this isn't the way it's supposed to be

162
00:09:11,580 --> 00:09:14,260
that's straight out of Augustine's theology

163
00:09:14,260 --> 00:09:17,320
coming out of Danny Glover in 1991

164
00:09:17,320 --> 00:09:21,040
that's theology when you look for it in different places

165
00:09:21,040 --> 00:09:24,860
it's a vandalism of shalom

166
00:09:24,860 --> 00:09:29,280
it's a vandalism of the way things are supposed to be

167
00:09:29,280 --> 00:09:30,440
that's evil

168
00:09:31,040 --> 00:09:34,240
Some would ask me, though, what about catastrophes on our planet?

169
00:09:34,440 --> 00:09:35,200
Are those evil?

170
00:09:35,500 --> 00:09:37,840
What about a tornado that rips through a town

171
00:09:37,840 --> 00:09:41,740
or a hailstorm that decimates a car and wipes out a neighborhood?

172
00:09:42,140 --> 00:09:43,640
What about those kinds of things,

173
00:09:43,680 --> 00:09:46,080
a cloudburst that tears apart a boat or something?

174
00:09:46,600 --> 00:09:48,480
What about those? Those are evil.

175
00:09:49,660 --> 00:09:51,400
And I want to say to those kinds of things

176
00:09:51,400 --> 00:09:55,520
that weather disasters are really a result of being on a planet

177
00:09:55,520 --> 00:09:58,780
that's rotating, that is tipped at 23 degrees,

178
00:09:58,780 --> 00:10:02,120
that has interactions of water and heat and storms.

179
00:10:02,560 --> 00:10:05,320
That's a result of the physics of our planet.

180
00:10:05,620 --> 00:10:08,540
The issue is those things are neutral in and of themselves.

181
00:10:08,920 --> 00:10:12,800
We interpret them as evil when human beings are hurt in some way

182
00:10:12,800 --> 00:10:14,620
as they encounter those experiences.

183
00:10:14,960 --> 00:10:18,480
But they're not necessarily evil in and of themselves.

184
00:10:19,200 --> 00:10:22,260
It's a matter of how we interpret the event.

185
00:10:24,480 --> 00:10:26,440
Can those things be sad? Absolutely.

186
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:30,250
But physics and chemistry has taken over.

187
00:10:31,150 --> 00:10:32,150
Are those gut-wrenching?

188
00:10:32,210 --> 00:10:33,310
They can be very gut-wrenching.

189
00:10:33,350 --> 00:10:34,570
But are they truly evil?

190
00:10:36,720 --> 00:10:38,640
If we acknowledge that evil and good exists,

191
00:10:39,720 --> 00:10:42,020
and that evil is a privation of the good,

192
00:10:42,460 --> 00:10:43,880
then where does evil come from?

193
00:10:43,900 --> 00:10:44,900
That's my second point.

194
00:10:45,440 --> 00:10:47,560
I want to talk about for a moment the origin of evil.

195
00:10:48,560 --> 00:10:49,440
The origin of evil.

196
00:10:49,440 --> 00:10:54,020
As we do this, I want to come back to these five basic fundamental concepts,

197
00:10:54,140 --> 00:10:55,140
and we've listed them for you.

198
00:10:55,620 --> 00:10:58,180
Christians believe in these five things.

199
00:10:59,060 --> 00:11:01,960
Number one, that God exists.

200
00:11:01,960 --> 00:11:04,450
if God exists.

201
00:11:05,200 --> 00:11:08,900
Number two, we affirm that God is all good.

202
00:11:11,380 --> 00:11:13,020
We would also want to affirm, number three,

203
00:11:13,140 --> 00:11:14,900
that God is all powerful.

204
00:11:16,780 --> 00:11:19,200
And number four, that He's all wise.

205
00:11:21,240 --> 00:11:25,160
We also have to affirm that evil does exist.

206
00:11:26,220 --> 00:11:28,560
And the challenge is, well, how do all five of those

207
00:11:28,560 --> 00:11:30,000
coexist together?

208
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:32,360
And as I've already mentioned, different religions

209
00:11:32,360 --> 00:11:35,580
and philosophical systems have tried numerous ways

210
00:11:35,580 --> 00:11:38,180
to work through those five points.

211
00:11:38,780 --> 00:11:41,720
Eastern religions will deny that evil is real at all.

212
00:11:42,500 --> 00:11:44,000
They'll say it's all inside your mind.

213
00:11:44,260 --> 00:11:45,580
Evil doesn't really exist.

214
00:11:45,960 --> 00:11:49,460
Some go so far as to say that pain doesn't really exist.

215
00:11:50,020 --> 00:11:52,200
It's all simply in the mind.

216
00:11:53,400 --> 00:11:55,700
Others claim that God is not good.

217
00:11:57,050 --> 00:11:59,890
Others would say that God is not all-powerful.

218
00:12:00,470 --> 00:12:03,430
That famous book that came out by Rabbi Kushner a while back,

219
00:12:03,970 --> 00:12:05,590
Bad Things Happen to Good People,

220
00:12:05,590 --> 00:12:10,570
his conclusion is that somehow God is not quite able to take care of evil.

221
00:12:11,110 --> 00:12:12,710
He's not quite in control.

222
00:12:15,220 --> 00:12:17,380
Yet the Bible affirms something different.

223
00:12:17,980 --> 00:12:22,980
So how do Christians maintain these five statements and make them not contradictory?

224
00:12:23,480 --> 00:12:28,100
If God is the creator of everything, doesn't that make God the author of evil?

225
00:12:29,990 --> 00:12:32,950
Dr. Peter Kreeft of Boston College makes this comment.

226
00:12:34,600 --> 00:12:38,780
And I'm going to quote a number of great theologians and professors here

227
00:12:38,780 --> 00:12:41,220
because they say it so much better than I ever could,

228
00:12:41,300 --> 00:12:43,920
and I want to give you the richness that comes from their minds.

229
00:12:44,280 --> 00:12:48,190
Dr. Peter Kreeft says, regarding God being all-powerful,

230
00:12:48,530 --> 00:12:50,850
that means he can do everything that is meaningful,

231
00:12:51,030 --> 00:12:52,230
everything that is possible,

232
00:12:52,670 --> 00:12:55,170
everything that makes any sense at all.

233
00:12:55,370 --> 00:12:58,850
But God cannot make himself to cease to exist.

234
00:13:00,140 --> 00:13:01,680
He cannot make good evil.

235
00:13:01,940 --> 00:13:03,820
There are certain things that don't make sense at all.

236
00:13:03,820 --> 00:13:06,460
Can God create a rock so heavy that he can't lift it?

237
00:13:06,520 --> 00:13:08,840
I mean, these are silly statements.

238
00:13:09,320 --> 00:13:10,660
They don't make any sense.

239
00:13:10,880 --> 00:13:12,520
They make sense in the English language,

240
00:13:12,620 --> 00:13:14,200
but they have no basis in reality.

241
00:13:17,350 --> 00:13:18,170
Now listen to this.

242
00:13:18,930 --> 00:13:23,390
God chose to create human beings with a free will.

243
00:13:24,930 --> 00:13:27,050
It is up to them rather than to God

244
00:13:27,050 --> 00:13:30,090
as to whether there was sin or not in the world.

245
00:13:30,450 --> 00:13:32,190
That's the nature of free will.

246
00:13:32,490 --> 00:13:35,070
Free will is when you have choices to make

247
00:13:35,070 --> 00:13:36,910
and when you choose the opposite of the good,

248
00:13:37,310 --> 00:13:38,450
evil enters into that.

249
00:13:38,450 --> 00:13:39,870
God makes human beings,

250
00:13:39,970 --> 00:13:41,550
and by creating them with the opportunity

251
00:13:41,550 --> 00:13:43,090
to choose evil.

252
00:13:43,850 --> 00:13:46,370
God has created the possibility of evil,

253
00:13:46,570 --> 00:13:49,590
but it is human beings that set evil in motion.

254
00:13:50,270 --> 00:13:52,710
It is human beings who do wrong.

255
00:13:53,270 --> 00:13:54,870
Norman Geisler said it this way,

256
00:13:55,590 --> 00:13:57,450
God created the fact of freedom

257
00:13:57,450 --> 00:14:00,710
and man performs the acts of freedom.

258
00:14:01,550 --> 00:14:03,170
God made evil possible.

259
00:14:03,610 --> 00:14:05,490
Creatures make it actual.

260
00:14:05,850 --> 00:14:10,340
If God had not allowed us to choose evil,

261
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:13,120
if God had created us in such a way

262
00:14:13,120 --> 00:14:17,560
that we could not truly sin or to go wrong.

263
00:14:18,600 --> 00:14:20,760
We would cease to be human beings.

264
00:14:23,700 --> 00:14:25,740
How many of you saw Steven Spielberg's film this summer,

265
00:14:25,840 --> 00:14:26,680
Artificial Intelligence?

266
00:14:28,360 --> 00:14:28,720
Nobody.

267
00:14:29,420 --> 00:14:30,120
I saw it.

268
00:14:30,160 --> 00:14:30,520
Two of you.

269
00:14:30,560 --> 00:14:31,480
Well, let me tell you what happens.

270
00:14:33,920 --> 00:14:35,180
The plot is simply this.

271
00:14:36,130 --> 00:14:37,810
It's the future not too far away,

272
00:14:37,850 --> 00:14:38,870
and they make a little boy,

273
00:14:39,980 --> 00:14:42,620
beautiful little robot automaton boy.

274
00:14:43,580 --> 00:14:45,100
And the whole struggle in the film is

275
00:14:45,100 --> 00:14:47,100
as he has some kind of conscious awareness,

276
00:14:47,780 --> 00:14:49,680
He's trying to find out what it means to be human.

277
00:14:49,780 --> 00:14:53,500
It's a play on the whole Pinocchio theme all over again, set into the future.

278
00:14:54,730 --> 00:14:58,970
But the striking thing is this, no matter how cute and how well programmed this little robot is,

279
00:14:58,970 --> 00:15:01,190
he truly is not human.

280
00:15:01,710 --> 00:15:05,770
He truly is not able to fully choose in his own free will.

281
00:15:05,990 --> 00:15:09,710
He's programmed by the programmers to do certain behaviors.

282
00:15:11,300 --> 00:15:14,620
And he's charming and he's cute, and if you see the film, he never blinks his eyes,

283
00:15:14,720 --> 00:15:16,020
and it's interesting how they do that.

284
00:15:16,020 --> 00:15:19,050
but he's not truly human

285
00:15:19,050 --> 00:15:22,010
because he cannot truly choose

286
00:15:22,010 --> 00:15:26,100
and he does not have the capacity

287
00:15:26,100 --> 00:15:27,960
to truly love.

288
00:15:28,540 --> 00:15:31,280
He's programmed to search after mother.

289
00:15:31,540 --> 00:15:34,420
He's programmed to have certain behaviors

290
00:15:34,420 --> 00:15:36,180
that we think are cute and cuddly

291
00:15:36,180 --> 00:15:37,320
and all those things

292
00:15:37,320 --> 00:15:39,460
but he's really not choosing to love

293
00:15:39,460 --> 00:15:41,180
out of himself as a person

294
00:15:41,180 --> 00:15:42,960
because he's not a person

295
00:15:42,960 --> 00:15:44,480
and that's the distinction

296
00:15:44,480 --> 00:15:46,080
between robots and human beings

297
00:15:46,080 --> 00:15:49,040
and God saw fit to make us human beings,

298
00:15:49,340 --> 00:15:51,720
truly able to love and to choose.

299
00:15:52,020 --> 00:15:56,860
But in so doing, we can choose to not love and to do evil.

300
00:15:58,090 --> 00:15:59,390
Evil then comes from choices,

301
00:15:59,550 --> 00:16:01,090
to abandon the good in the right way.

302
00:16:02,280 --> 00:16:04,800
In that sense, evil is our problem, not God's problem.

303
00:16:05,580 --> 00:16:06,940
God is not the author of evil.

304
00:16:07,260 --> 00:16:10,160
We are the author of evil in the misuse of our free will.

305
00:16:13,260 --> 00:16:15,600
Number three, I want to cover the purpose of evil.

306
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:17,560
You may never have thought about evil

307
00:16:17,560 --> 00:16:19,260
in terms of having a purpose.

308
00:16:20,400 --> 00:16:22,600
Peter Kreeft again asks this question.

309
00:16:23,440 --> 00:16:25,700
How can a mere finite human being

310
00:16:25,700 --> 00:16:28,140
be sure that infinite wisdom

311
00:16:28,140 --> 00:16:32,040
would not tolerate certain short-range evils

312
00:16:32,040 --> 00:16:34,200
for more long-range goods

313
00:16:34,200 --> 00:16:35,820
that we cannot foresee?

314
00:16:37,190 --> 00:16:38,110
Let me say that again.

315
00:16:38,110 --> 00:16:40,510
How can we as finite minds

316
00:16:40,510 --> 00:16:44,240
be sure that a God of infinite wisdom

317
00:16:44,240 --> 00:16:47,460
would not tolerate certain short-range evils

318
00:16:47,460 --> 00:16:49,640
in order for more long-range goods

319
00:16:49,640 --> 00:16:51,740
that we can't see?

320
00:16:52,400 --> 00:16:54,300
How do we know that isn't happening?

321
00:16:54,560 --> 00:16:56,380
We can't prove it, but I think we can say

322
00:16:56,380 --> 00:16:57,580
we don't know.

323
00:16:58,660 --> 00:16:59,300
We don't know.

324
00:16:59,840 --> 00:17:02,020
And now we're tapping into the realm of God's goodness

325
00:17:02,020 --> 00:17:03,100
and His perfect knowledge.

326
00:17:03,380 --> 00:17:06,400
If God is truly all-wise and He knows all things,

327
00:17:06,400 --> 00:17:09,460
He knows the present and the future and the past.

328
00:17:09,720 --> 00:17:12,080
For time is just one dimension of our universe

329
00:17:12,080 --> 00:17:15,040
and we're arguing that God is outside of space and time.

330
00:17:15,300 --> 00:17:18,000
Then is it not possible that He can see the whole big picture

331
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:20,660
and would tolerate certain short-term evils

332
00:17:20,660 --> 00:17:23,020
for long-term goods.

333
00:17:25,240 --> 00:17:27,060
You see, our minds can't fathom yet

334
00:17:27,060 --> 00:17:28,760
an infinite mind of God.

335
00:17:29,880 --> 00:17:31,400
Dr. Norman Geisler says this,

336
00:17:31,460 --> 00:17:33,540
we do know some good purposes for evil,

337
00:17:33,960 --> 00:17:35,680
to warn us of greater evil,

338
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:37,660
to keep us from self-destruction,

339
00:17:37,920 --> 00:17:39,980
to help bring about greater goods

340
00:17:39,980 --> 00:17:40,920
and to defeat evil.

341
00:17:41,420 --> 00:17:43,840
If a finite mind can discover

342
00:17:43,840 --> 00:17:45,760
some good purpose for evil,

343
00:17:46,120 --> 00:17:48,140
surely an infinite good and wise God

344
00:17:48,140 --> 00:17:50,780
has a good purpose for all suffering.

345
00:17:52,590 --> 00:17:53,850
So what's the definition of good?

346
00:17:54,900 --> 00:17:57,040
Does good mean the absence of pain or suffering?

347
00:17:58,190 --> 00:17:59,990
On the surface, we want to say yes,

348
00:18:00,130 --> 00:18:01,810
but the more I've thought about it and read about it,

349
00:18:01,810 --> 00:18:02,430
I don't think so.

350
00:18:03,170 --> 00:18:05,450
The other day, Mario Sensei is not here.

351
00:18:06,070 --> 00:18:07,290
He's at a tournament this morning.

352
00:18:07,770 --> 00:18:09,750
But Sensei Mario in our karate ministry

353
00:18:09,750 --> 00:18:12,090
was really working us very hard.

354
00:18:13,100 --> 00:18:14,100
In fact, let's be honest,

355
00:18:14,100 --> 00:18:15,820
he had me absolutely dripping

356
00:18:15,820 --> 00:18:18,660
and about ready to collapse on the floor after the workout.

357
00:18:18,660 --> 00:18:22,720
I mean, he pushed me in places I had never known that I could go.

358
00:18:22,920 --> 00:18:27,140
He stretched my muscles and made me do things in contortant ways I never knew I could go.

359
00:18:27,640 --> 00:18:28,860
He pushed us.

360
00:18:29,200 --> 00:18:31,340
And I'll tell you, I was in great pain.

361
00:18:32,020 --> 00:18:36,760
And when I limped out of here to my car, I mean, I hobbled down the steps and got home

362
00:18:36,760 --> 00:18:38,660
and collapsed when I got home.

363
00:18:38,820 --> 00:18:39,840
I was in great pain.

364
00:18:40,020 --> 00:18:41,340
But was that an evil?

365
00:18:42,760 --> 00:18:47,420
In fact, that pain was actually making me better at a sport that I had committed to.

366
00:18:48,940 --> 00:18:51,720
Some pains can push us to good things.

367
00:18:53,980 --> 00:18:54,780
Oh, that's a blue button.

368
00:18:54,860 --> 00:18:55,280
What do you know?

369
00:18:57,240 --> 00:18:58,420
I'm really preaching now.

370
00:19:00,890 --> 00:19:02,230
Dr. Kreeft says this.

371
00:19:02,570 --> 00:19:05,330
Dentists, athletes, trainers, teachers, parents,

372
00:19:05,570 --> 00:19:07,930
they all know that sometimes to be good

373
00:19:07,930 --> 00:19:09,550
is not to be kind.

374
00:19:11,470 --> 00:19:13,730
Certainly there are times when God allows suffering

375
00:19:13,730 --> 00:19:16,210
and deprives us of the lesser good of pleasure

376
00:19:16,210 --> 00:19:18,770
in order to help us toward the greater good

377
00:19:18,770 --> 00:19:21,790
of moral and spiritual education.

378
00:19:23,080 --> 00:19:28,320
Sometimes pain teaches us things and pushes us to greater goods and to greater heights.

379
00:19:28,680 --> 00:19:33,000
I read this week about, in Dr. Paul Brand's book called The Gift of Pain,

380
00:19:33,080 --> 00:19:35,240
he was a physician and spent a lot of time in India.

381
00:19:35,780 --> 00:19:41,220
And as he's working on people with leprosy, he's talking about the gift of pain.

382
00:19:42,210 --> 00:19:45,110
And what's intriguing is the beginning of the book starts off with this little girl

383
00:19:45,110 --> 00:19:49,390
that has this genetic deformity where she cannot feel pain at all.

384
00:19:50,090 --> 00:19:52,770
When she's swat on the behind from mom and dad, it tickles.

385
00:19:53,130 --> 00:19:56,410
When she sticks a pin into her thumb, she feels no pain.

386
00:19:58,740 --> 00:20:01,740
And they call her, over time, a monster.

387
00:20:02,040 --> 00:20:05,700
Because this little child does not know when she is hurting herself.

388
00:20:05,700 --> 00:20:10,240
And when she bumps things and steps on things and things lodge into her feet,

389
00:20:10,520 --> 00:20:13,060
she has no sensation of the pain.

390
00:20:13,540 --> 00:20:18,160
And as the years go on, she's literally losing her fingers and her face

391
00:20:18,160 --> 00:20:21,540
because she destroys herself and does not know it.

392
00:20:22,140 --> 00:20:24,940
Pain does not prevent her from doing certain things

393
00:20:24,940 --> 00:20:25,940
and entering into places.

394
00:20:26,220 --> 00:20:28,380
She could stick her hand in the fire and burn her hand off,

395
00:20:28,380 --> 00:20:30,760
and it would not feel the pain.

396
00:20:33,710 --> 00:20:36,350
By 14, she had lost both legs and most of her fingers.

397
00:20:37,090 --> 00:20:42,790
And Dr. Brand is suggesting that pain is and can be a gift to us,

398
00:20:43,030 --> 00:20:46,490
for it prevents us from harming ourselves in grander ways

399
00:20:46,490 --> 00:20:49,730
and protects us.

400
00:20:51,120 --> 00:20:53,120
Emotional pain also does something similar.

401
00:20:54,360 --> 00:20:57,420
See, emotional pain will point to something that's wrong.

402
00:20:57,940 --> 00:21:03,000
Emotional pain is a signal that something is wrong and needs to be dealt with.

403
00:21:03,620 --> 00:21:08,860
When we insulate ourselves with emotional pain, we do damage to our souls and to our minds.

404
00:21:08,860 --> 00:21:11,520
But we don't deal with the real problem.

405
00:21:12,420 --> 00:21:14,640
And so to speak, we stay sick.

406
00:21:15,340 --> 00:21:16,920
We don't grow through an issue.

407
00:21:17,560 --> 00:21:18,800
We only avoid it.

408
00:21:18,800 --> 00:21:23,720
If we anesthetize ourselves through alcohol and drugs and pornography and all these sorts of things,

409
00:21:23,960 --> 00:21:26,060
we never deal with the emotional pain in our lives.

410
00:21:26,300 --> 00:21:28,580
We never grow and expand and become healthy.

411
00:21:28,800 --> 00:21:32,200
We just stay numb and sick and stuck.

412
00:21:32,300 --> 00:21:36,780
And so you see, emotional pain can actually push us and grow.

413
00:21:37,260 --> 00:21:39,200
And is that not good?

414
00:21:41,160 --> 00:21:45,540
As I said before, God is not ultimately interested in our comfort, but in our character.

415
00:21:45,820 --> 00:21:48,520
The Apostle Paul writes this in Romans chapter 5.

416
00:21:49,420 --> 00:21:52,920
Therefore, since we have been made right in God's sight by faith,

417
00:21:53,460 --> 00:21:58,020
we have peace with God because of what Jesus Christ, our Lord, has done for us.

418
00:21:58,580 --> 00:22:02,440
Because of our faith, Christ has brought us to this place of highest privilege

419
00:22:02,440 --> 00:22:08,160
where we now stand and we confidently and joyfully look forward to sharing God's glory.

420
00:22:08,800 --> 00:22:12,000
We can rejoice, too, when we run into problems and trials,

421
00:22:12,140 --> 00:22:13,900
for we know that they are good for us.

422
00:22:13,900 --> 00:22:19,540
They help us to learn to endure, and endurance develops strength of character in us.

423
00:22:20,200 --> 00:22:23,960
And character strengthens our confident expectation of salvation.

424
00:22:24,820 --> 00:22:29,200
And this expectation will not disappoint us, for we know how dearly God loves us

425
00:22:29,200 --> 00:22:34,360
because he has given us the Holy Spirit to fill our hearts with his love.

426
00:22:37,070 --> 00:22:38,010
Think about this.

427
00:22:39,120 --> 00:22:41,280
Even Jesus, God's own Son,

428
00:22:41,980 --> 00:22:46,160
was not immune from suffering while on this earth.

429
00:22:47,570 --> 00:22:48,870
Hebrews 5.8 says,

430
00:22:50,120 --> 00:22:52,060
So even though Jesus was God's Son,

431
00:22:52,990 --> 00:22:56,890
He learned obedience from the things that He suffered.

432
00:22:59,200 --> 00:23:01,820
Even God's own Son was not immune

433
00:23:01,820 --> 00:23:04,620
from the pain of living on this earth.

434
00:23:04,620 --> 00:23:06,380
If Jesus was not exempt,

435
00:23:06,780 --> 00:23:10,100
why do we think we should be exempt as well?

436
00:23:13,030 --> 00:23:15,330
One question that gets raised is this.

437
00:23:16,290 --> 00:23:18,430
Why doesn't God intervene now

438
00:23:18,430 --> 00:23:20,750
and deal with all the evil right now?

439
00:23:22,120 --> 00:23:23,640
I think, frankly, if God were to come

440
00:23:23,640 --> 00:23:24,880
and deal with evil right now,

441
00:23:24,960 --> 00:23:26,340
the world would simply be over.

442
00:23:26,640 --> 00:23:28,480
The evil in my heart would be purged out.

443
00:23:28,720 --> 00:23:30,180
The evil in your heart would be purged.

444
00:23:30,480 --> 00:23:31,900
And quite frankly, we'd all be gone.

445
00:23:31,960 --> 00:23:32,660
It would all be over.

446
00:23:32,740 --> 00:23:33,420
It would all be done.

447
00:23:33,540 --> 00:23:34,340
History would be over.

448
00:23:34,620 --> 00:23:35,980
Is that what we truly want?

449
00:23:37,420 --> 00:23:39,120
2 Peter 3 says this.

450
00:23:39,860 --> 00:23:41,620
The Lord isn't really being slow

451
00:23:41,620 --> 00:23:43,220
about His promise to return.

452
00:23:43,220 --> 00:23:45,240
as some people think.

453
00:23:46,160 --> 00:23:48,140
No, he's being patient for your sake.

454
00:23:48,580 --> 00:23:51,100
He does not want anyone to perish.

455
00:23:51,460 --> 00:23:54,160
So he is giving more time for everyone to repent.

456
00:23:55,120 --> 00:23:56,240
But the day of the Lord will come

457
00:23:56,240 --> 00:23:57,780
as unexpectedly as a thief.

458
00:23:58,360 --> 00:24:00,640
And the heavens will pass away with a terrible noise.

459
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:03,040
And everything in them will disappear in fire.

460
00:24:03,040 --> 00:24:05,040
And the earth and everything on it

461
00:24:05,040 --> 00:24:07,080
will be exposed to judgment.

462
00:24:08,380 --> 00:24:11,420
God will deal with injustice and with evil

463
00:24:11,420 --> 00:24:12,940
at the right time.

464
00:24:12,940 --> 00:24:17,980
And he is waiting for that judgment so that others may still come and know him

465
00:24:17,980 --> 00:24:21,820
before he finally deals completely with evil.

466
00:24:23,310 --> 00:24:25,770
But still, Kirk, good people suffer. Why?

467
00:24:27,560 --> 00:24:30,180
Another question. Are we really that good?

468
00:24:31,320 --> 00:24:32,900
We all bear the stain of sin.

469
00:24:33,500 --> 00:24:36,240
In God's eyes, we're all sinful creatures worthy of destruction.

470
00:24:36,740 --> 00:24:41,760
Sometimes pain is what it takes to wake us up and to bring us back to God himself.

471
00:24:41,760 --> 00:24:44,380
Where we can then repent and find forgiveness.

472
00:24:44,380 --> 00:24:46,740
C.S. Lewis said in a very famous phrase,

473
00:24:48,040 --> 00:24:49,020
and I put it up here for you,

474
00:24:49,660 --> 00:24:51,620
God whispers to us in our pleasures,

475
00:24:52,860 --> 00:24:54,500
speaks to us in our conscience,

476
00:24:55,060 --> 00:24:56,740
but he shouts in our pains.

477
00:24:57,780 --> 00:25:00,940
It's his megaphone to rouse a deaf world.

478
00:25:03,520 --> 00:25:05,500
Where is God in the midst of pain, we ask?

479
00:25:06,520 --> 00:25:07,620
And we ask that question,

480
00:25:07,740 --> 00:25:10,820
somehow we're saying that God somehow does not feel pain,

481
00:25:10,880 --> 00:25:13,020
that he's somehow removed from our plight,

482
00:25:13,100 --> 00:25:13,980
from our situation.

483
00:25:14,300 --> 00:25:16,220
But precisely the opposite is the case,

484
00:25:16,220 --> 00:25:20,980
For instead of abandoning the world of pain, God embraced it and entered into it.

485
00:25:21,200 --> 00:25:26,160
In Jesus Christ, God entered into this world, our four-dimensional space-time,

486
00:25:26,540 --> 00:25:32,000
and felt and experiences the reality that we all experience, and part of that is pain.

487
00:25:34,170 --> 00:25:37,610
Jesus faced the realities of life in Palestine 2,000 years ago.

488
00:25:38,030 --> 00:25:41,650
Jesus was hungry and thirsty and tired.

489
00:25:42,010 --> 00:25:46,630
Jesus faced loneliness and betrayal and the agonizing death of friends.

490
00:25:46,630 --> 00:25:49,250
He wept over the death of Lazarus.

491
00:25:49,750 --> 00:25:53,170
He understood what it meant to lose somebody to death.

492
00:25:54,420 --> 00:25:58,320
And then he faced the shame and the humiliation of a false trial,

493
00:25:58,700 --> 00:26:03,040
of beating with fists the lacerations of a cat o' nine tails on his back,

494
00:26:03,220 --> 00:26:07,340
and then ultimately he died the shameful death on a Roman cross,

495
00:26:07,680 --> 00:26:11,920
which is simply the instrument of capital punishment of the day.

496
00:26:13,250 --> 00:26:15,150
Friends, God is not immune to pain.

497
00:26:15,150 --> 00:26:18,710
and God used that pain and death of his son

498
00:26:18,710 --> 00:26:20,490
for our good

499
00:26:20,490 --> 00:26:23,430
that we might be forgiven our moral debts

500
00:26:23,430 --> 00:26:24,630
towards God.

501
00:26:28,320 --> 00:26:29,460
One more thought on this subject.

502
00:26:31,040 --> 00:26:33,900
There is something I want to say boldly about suffering

503
00:26:33,900 --> 00:26:37,780
that actually draws Christians closer to God

504
00:26:37,780 --> 00:26:39,080
in the long run

505
00:26:39,080 --> 00:26:40,480
and the question becomes

506
00:26:40,480 --> 00:26:43,340
is that not ultimately good?

507
00:26:45,630 --> 00:26:47,530
You might think that those who suffer

508
00:26:47,530 --> 00:26:48,910
would be driven from God

509
00:26:48,910 --> 00:26:50,610
and to some people that can happen.

510
00:26:50,810 --> 00:27:01,640
But as you spend more time with people, you realize that sometimes and often that pain and suffering can actually drive us to God more powerfully than anything else.

511
00:27:03,220 --> 00:27:12,480
And you find that people who have suffered, there's a richness in their life, there's a depth of their spirit with God that those who have not suffered much simply do not share.

512
00:27:14,140 --> 00:27:16,060
And is that not ultimately good?

513
00:27:16,380 --> 00:27:25,850
To bring some perspective on this, I want to take a look at the life of the most famous sufferer, the biblical character Job.

514
00:27:27,180 --> 00:27:29,220
We looked at a contemporary version of his life.

515
00:27:29,360 --> 00:27:30,740
I want to go back into the Old Testament.

516
00:27:32,660 --> 00:27:35,100
The book of Job is possibly the oldest book in the Bible,

517
00:27:35,240 --> 00:27:37,140
but it reads as if it were written yesterday.

518
00:27:38,020 --> 00:27:40,160
It tackles the great problem of suffering.

519
00:27:41,270 --> 00:27:44,650
But the book of Job is also about faith in its purest form.

520
00:27:45,570 --> 00:27:47,430
In the midst of calamity and confusion,

521
00:27:47,570 --> 00:27:50,410
we see his faith holding on by the fingernails.

522
00:27:50,410 --> 00:27:52,510
The quick summary of Job is this.

523
00:27:53,150 --> 00:27:57,410
The greatest man in all the East lost, very quickly, 7,000 sheep.

524
00:27:57,530 --> 00:28:02,870
3,000 camels, 5,000 oxen, 500 donkeys, and numerous servants.

525
00:28:03,330 --> 00:28:05,270
Then, on top of that, all of Job's children,

526
00:28:05,450 --> 00:28:06,690
seven sons and three daughters,

527
00:28:06,810 --> 00:28:08,990
died in a mysterious and mighty gust of wind.

528
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:11,620
And then his health finally fails,

529
00:28:11,760 --> 00:28:15,100
and he's got sores that break out all over his body, head to foot.

530
00:28:16,280 --> 00:28:19,120
Job went from being on top to being on the bottom,

531
00:28:19,360 --> 00:28:21,700
just like that, overnight, immediately.

532
00:28:22,200 --> 00:28:24,720
A man had the world in his hands,

533
00:28:24,720 --> 00:28:27,780
who's now on the bottom, to be truly pitied.

534
00:28:28,040 --> 00:28:36,970
But what Job doesn't know is that whole predicament gets started over a type of wager, so to speak, between God and Satan.

535
00:28:36,970 --> 00:28:43,690
The issue is, does Job really love God because of the blessings of God, or does he truly love Him from his soul?

536
00:28:45,440 --> 00:28:53,430
And once the calamities hit, Job prods him. Job's wife, rather, prods him to simply curse God and die.

537
00:28:54,030 --> 00:28:54,950
But Job refuses.

538
00:28:55,830 --> 00:28:58,310
And for the next 35 chapters of that book,

539
00:28:58,670 --> 00:29:02,390
Job and his friends try to make sense out of his predicament.

540
00:29:02,630 --> 00:29:06,710
They try and figure out what has he done to deserve all of this.

541
00:29:06,790 --> 00:29:11,730
And they wrestle with how can there be so much suffering if God is truly up there.

542
00:29:13,650 --> 00:29:17,750
But what they don't know is the first two chapters give this inside look.

543
00:29:17,750 --> 00:29:24,450
They give the curtain pulling aside and we see that God is up to something far larger than what Job can perceive.

544
00:29:25,110 --> 00:29:28,550
God has a purpose and a plan far grander and larger

545
00:29:28,550 --> 00:29:32,390
than Job's experience inside our four-dimensional time-space.

546
00:29:33,420 --> 00:29:36,300
And what we learn from Job is this, amongst many other things,

547
00:29:37,000 --> 00:29:40,020
is that faith matters in the spiritual world.

548
00:29:40,020 --> 00:29:43,940
That faith matters in God's realm.

549
00:29:45,120 --> 00:29:48,700
There are many great themes going on outside of our perception.

550
00:29:49,180 --> 00:29:51,620
As we've said earlier, there can be purposes for evil,

551
00:29:51,620 --> 00:29:53,480
purposes for a greater good

552
00:29:53,480 --> 00:29:55,280
that God in his ultimate power

553
00:29:55,280 --> 00:29:57,300
and knowledge and wisdom can see

554
00:29:57,300 --> 00:29:59,200
but that we don't see.

555
00:30:00,630 --> 00:30:02,450
Friends, there are things going on in the spiritual realm

556
00:30:02,450 --> 00:30:04,270
that we have no idea about

557
00:30:04,270 --> 00:30:06,090
but it doesn't mean that they are not there

558
00:30:06,090 --> 00:30:07,090
and don't exist.

559
00:30:10,550 --> 00:30:12,210
The book of Job wraps up like this.

560
00:30:13,280 --> 00:30:14,720
After all of Job's laments

561
00:30:14,720 --> 00:30:15,820
and all of his questions,

562
00:30:15,980 --> 00:30:18,080
God finally in chapter 38

563
00:30:18,080 --> 00:30:20,400
finally answers and here's what he says.

564
00:30:22,040 --> 00:30:23,920
And the Lord answered Job from the whirlwind.

565
00:30:23,920 --> 00:30:26,640
After 35 chapters of complaining, here it comes.

566
00:30:27,120 --> 00:30:31,880
Who is this, says God, that questions my wisdom with such ignorant words?

567
00:30:32,440 --> 00:30:36,680
Brace yourself, because I have some questions for you, and you must answer them.

568
00:30:37,020 --> 00:30:40,760
Where were you when I laid the foundations of the earth?

569
00:30:41,040 --> 00:30:43,220
Tell me if you know so much.

570
00:30:45,400 --> 00:30:50,740
And then he goes on, and he tells about his miracles, about creation, about the animals and the beasts,

571
00:30:51,020 --> 00:30:53,420
and all of these marvelous things that God has created.

572
00:30:53,420 --> 00:30:58,210
And then in Job 42, Job finally replies to the Lord,

573
00:30:58,770 --> 00:31:02,370
I know that you can do anything and no one can stop you.

574
00:31:02,730 --> 00:31:05,930
You ask, who is this that questions my wisdom with such ignorance?

575
00:31:06,170 --> 00:31:06,730
It is I.

576
00:31:07,230 --> 00:31:09,950
And I was talking about things I did not understand,

577
00:31:10,110 --> 00:31:12,150
things far too wonderful for me.

578
00:31:12,730 --> 00:31:14,650
You said, listen and I will speak.

579
00:31:14,750 --> 00:31:16,850
I have some questions for you and you must answer them.

580
00:31:17,470 --> 00:31:21,850
I had heard about you before, but now I've seen you with my own eyes.

581
00:31:21,850 --> 00:31:24,250
I take back everything I said.

582
00:31:24,690 --> 00:31:28,910
I sit in dust and ashes to show my repentance.

583
00:31:32,240 --> 00:31:33,800
From Job's perspective,

584
00:31:34,900 --> 00:31:36,980
God does not seem to be all-powerful

585
00:31:36,980 --> 00:31:40,040
because all of these awful things are happening to Job.

586
00:31:40,500 --> 00:31:43,300
And yet God defends himself by describing

587
00:31:43,300 --> 00:31:44,960
that he's the creator of all things,

588
00:31:45,180 --> 00:31:48,040
that he is indeed in control and is all-powerful.

589
00:31:48,300 --> 00:31:51,520
And at the end of the book, Job realizes that and says,

590
00:31:51,520 --> 00:31:54,200
I'm sorry, I take it all back.

591
00:31:54,380 --> 00:31:57,200
you are God and I am not.

592
00:31:58,930 --> 00:31:59,990
At the end of the book of Job,

593
00:32:00,070 --> 00:32:01,710
the intriguing thing for us is this.

594
00:32:01,790 --> 00:32:03,010
As the reader of the book,

595
00:32:03,870 --> 00:32:07,230
no matter all the question of the whys of the suffering

596
00:32:07,230 --> 00:32:10,110
and all the issues about is God fair or not,

597
00:32:10,350 --> 00:32:11,750
the book of Job does this.

598
00:32:12,030 --> 00:32:13,990
It simply deflects the question

599
00:32:13,990 --> 00:32:16,150
and focuses on our response.

600
00:32:16,510 --> 00:32:19,190
It doesn't go into all the whys of the calamity.

601
00:32:19,190 --> 00:32:23,390
It simply talks now about what is your response to God.

602
00:32:25,340 --> 00:32:28,000
Philip Yancey, in his book, Disappointment with God, said this.

603
00:32:28,800 --> 00:32:34,820
At the end, when he heard the voice from the whirlwind, Job finally attained that faith.

604
00:32:35,830 --> 00:32:40,990
God reeled off natural phenomena, the solar system, constellations, thunderstorms, wild animals,

605
00:32:40,990 --> 00:32:47,500
and Job could not begin to explain, if you can't comprehend the visible world you live in,

606
00:32:47,960 --> 00:32:53,540
how dare you expect to comprehend a world that you cannot even see.

607
00:32:54,950 --> 00:32:56,850
And conscious of that big picture,

608
00:32:57,310 --> 00:32:59,870
Job in the end repents in dust and ashes.

609
00:33:01,510 --> 00:33:02,870
Remember what Peter Kreef said,

610
00:33:03,130 --> 00:33:06,710
how can a finite mind be sure that infinite wisdom

611
00:33:06,710 --> 00:33:09,790
would not tolerate certain short-range evils

612
00:33:09,790 --> 00:33:12,390
in order for more long-range goods

613
00:33:12,390 --> 00:33:14,430
that we simply can't foresee?

614
00:33:17,850 --> 00:33:19,190
I quote Philip Yancey again.

615
00:33:23,000 --> 00:33:24,540
Very often, disappointment with God

616
00:33:24,540 --> 00:33:26,960
begins in Job-like circumstances.

617
00:33:27,120 --> 00:33:28,960
The death of a child, a tragic accident,

618
00:33:28,960 --> 00:33:35,320
a loss of a job. These all can bring on the questions that Job asks. Why me? What does God

619
00:33:35,320 --> 00:33:42,720
have against me? Why does he seem so distant? And as readers of Job's story, we can see behind the

620
00:33:42,720 --> 00:33:49,790
curtain to a context being waged in the invisible world. But in our own trials, we don't have that

621
00:33:49,790 --> 00:33:54,990
insight. We can't see into realms that are not open to us. When tragedy strikes, we're going to

622
00:33:54,990 --> 00:34:02,670
live in the shadow, unaware of what is transpiring in the unseen world. The drama that Job lived out

623
00:34:02,670 --> 00:34:10,170
will then replicate itself in our individual lives. And once again, God will let his reputation ride

624
00:34:10,170 --> 00:34:17,920
on the response of unpredictable human beings. Friends, we see the physical world as real

625
00:34:17,920 --> 00:34:24,880
and the unseen world as somehow unreal. Perhaps it is more the other way around.

626
00:34:24,880 --> 00:34:29,740
Perhaps, really, reality is in a realm that we cannot perceive,

627
00:34:29,900 --> 00:34:34,540
and this is real but less real in the spiritual realm that God inhabits

628
00:34:34,540 --> 00:34:37,460
and where things are going on that we cannot see.

629
00:34:41,060 --> 00:34:43,020
Peter Kreeft finally concludes and says,

630
00:34:43,700 --> 00:34:46,580
God didn't let Job suffer because he lacked love,

631
00:34:47,270 --> 00:34:49,590
but because he did love.

632
00:34:50,090 --> 00:34:53,650
In order to bring Job to the point of encountering God face to face,

633
00:34:54,010 --> 00:34:56,330
which is humanity's supreme happiness,

634
00:34:57,290 --> 00:34:59,850
Job's suffering hollowed out a big space in him

635
00:34:59,850 --> 00:35:07,080
so that God and joy could fill it.

636
00:35:09,500 --> 00:35:10,580
Let's review for a moment.

637
00:35:11,660 --> 00:35:13,160
Christians believe five things.

638
00:35:13,860 --> 00:35:14,680
God exists.

639
00:35:15,900 --> 00:35:16,700
God is all good.

640
00:35:17,660 --> 00:35:18,860
God is all powerful.

641
00:35:19,700 --> 00:35:20,840
He's all wise.

642
00:35:22,000 --> 00:35:24,100
And that evil does exist.

643
00:35:24,580 --> 00:35:28,260
Can you now begin to at least be open to see

644
00:35:28,260 --> 00:35:30,880
how those beliefs are still held together.

645
00:35:31,480 --> 00:35:33,640
The highest good that God has determined

646
00:35:33,640 --> 00:35:36,260
is that free creatures, human beings,

647
00:35:36,360 --> 00:35:39,420
created in freedom to choose God and to love Him,

648
00:35:39,660 --> 00:35:42,900
even if that means that evil is a potential reality

649
00:35:42,900 --> 00:35:44,820
that can be exercised.

650
00:35:45,870 --> 00:35:48,710
And God can even use that for higher purposes.

651
00:35:51,820 --> 00:35:53,640
Finally, friends, the answer to suffering

652
00:35:53,640 --> 00:35:55,240
is not a philosophical answer.

653
00:35:55,940 --> 00:35:58,760
The answer to suffering is not really contorting our minds

654
00:35:58,760 --> 00:36:00,240
in different ways to understand it.

655
00:36:00,560 --> 00:36:03,880
The answer to suffering ultimately is a person,

656
00:36:04,260 --> 00:36:06,840
and it's the person of Jesus Christ.

657
00:36:07,400 --> 00:36:10,600
God come in humanity to actually experience

658
00:36:10,600 --> 00:36:13,320
and embrace our suffering.

659
00:36:15,700 --> 00:36:18,080
I finish with this quote from John Stott,

660
00:36:18,620 --> 00:36:21,200
one of the greatest contemporary theologians

661
00:36:21,200 --> 00:36:23,560
and statesmen in the Christian church today,

662
00:36:25,080 --> 00:36:26,260
and he says this,

663
00:36:26,340 --> 00:36:28,000
and I've put it up here for you to read with me.

664
00:36:29,290 --> 00:36:31,770
I could never myself believe in God

665
00:36:31,770 --> 00:36:34,620
if it were not for the cross.

666
00:36:35,700 --> 00:36:37,140
In the real world of pain,

667
00:36:37,260 --> 00:36:39,640
how could one worship a God who is immune to it?

668
00:36:40,410 --> 00:36:42,150
I have entered many Buddhist temples

669
00:36:42,150 --> 00:36:43,670
in different Asian countries

670
00:36:43,670 --> 00:36:45,750
and stood respectfully before the Buddha,

671
00:36:46,570 --> 00:36:49,010
his legs crossed, his arms folded,

672
00:36:49,590 --> 00:36:50,630
his eyes closed,

673
00:36:51,170 --> 00:36:53,730
the ghost of a smile playing round his mouth,

674
00:36:54,030 --> 00:36:55,590
a remote look on his face,

675
00:36:55,970 --> 00:36:59,030
detached from the agonies of the world.

676
00:36:59,780 --> 00:37:01,600
But each time, after a while,

677
00:37:01,600 --> 00:37:03,820
I've had to turn away he writes

678
00:37:03,820 --> 00:37:06,260
and in imagination I've turned

679
00:37:06,260 --> 00:37:07,980
instead to that lonely twisted

680
00:37:07,980 --> 00:37:09,620
tortured figure on the cross

681
00:37:09,620 --> 00:37:12,200
nails through hands and feet

682
00:37:12,200 --> 00:37:13,960
back lacerated

683
00:37:13,960 --> 00:37:15,800
limbs wrenched brow bleeding

684
00:37:15,800 --> 00:37:17,980
and thorn pricks mouth dry

685
00:37:17,980 --> 00:37:19,700
and intolerably thirsty

686
00:37:19,700 --> 00:37:21,940
plunged in God forsaken

687
00:37:21,940 --> 00:37:24,340
darkness that is the

688
00:37:24,340 --> 00:37:26,280
God for me he laid

689
00:37:26,280 --> 00:37:27,960
aside his immunity to pain

690
00:37:27,960 --> 00:37:30,240
he entered our world of flesh and

691
00:37:30,240 --> 00:37:39,200
blood, tears, and death. He suffered for us, and our sufferings become more manageable in light of

692
00:37:39,200 --> 00:37:45,770
his. There is still a question mark against human suffering, but over it we boldly stamp another

693
00:37:45,770 --> 00:37:54,460
mark, the cross, which symbolized divine suffering. The cross of Christ is God's only self-justification

694
00:37:54,460 --> 00:37:57,690
in such a world as ours.

695
00:37:59,700 --> 00:38:00,440
Father in heaven,

696
00:38:02,210 --> 00:38:03,270
these are heavy things.

697
00:38:05,670 --> 00:38:08,290
And Father, we still don't always understand

698
00:38:08,290 --> 00:38:09,550
suffering and how to deal with it.

